    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nThere is a change in Cython 3.3.0a1 that leads to a segfault with the example code\n\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\n\n```cython\ndef check(N: list[int]):\n    return any(n < 0 for n in N)\n\nclass A:\n    pass\n\ncheck([A()])\n```\nResult with Cython 3.3.0a1:\n```\n>>> import pyximport; pyximport.install()\n(None, <pyximport.pyximport.PyxImportMetaFinder object at 0x7238f521d400>)\n>>> import check\nSegmentation fault (core dumped)\n```\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\nPrevious Cython versions do not segfault and allow other types to pass through even though the annotation says int. With python-flint's fmpz integer type the code would still work.\n\nPossibly it should fail with an exception if the type is not int?\n\n### OS\n\nLinux x86-64\n\n### Python version\n\n3.13.1\n\n### Cython version\n\n3.3.0a1\n\n### Additional context\n\nThis popped up in CI in https://github.com/flintlib/python-flint/pull/405. The original problem was not a segfault but rather test failures like this:\n```\n___________________ test_docstrings[flint.types.fmpq_mpoly.fmpq_mpoly.deflation] ____________________\nflint.types.fmpq_mpoly.fmpq_mpoly.deflation, line: 1033\nFailed example:\n\tq.inflate(N) == f\nException raised:\n    Traceback (most recent call last):\n      File \"/.../uv/python/cpython-3.13.1-linux-x86_64-gnu/lib/python3.13/doctest.py\", line 1395, in __run\n        exec(compile(example.source, filename, \"single\",\n        ~~~~^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n                     compileflags, True), test.globs)\n                     ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n      File \"<doctest flint.types.fmpq_mpoly.fmpq_mpoly.deflation[5]>\", line 1, in <module>\n        q.inflate(N) == f\n        ~~~~~~~~~^^^\n      File \"flint/types/fmpq_mpoly.pyx\", line 997, in flint.types.fmpq_mpoly.fmpq_mpoly.inflate\n    ValueError: all inflate strides must be non-negative\n```\nBy the time I got down to a minimal reproducer it was a segfault so I'm not sure if that segfault is actually the same as the original problem I was investigating.",
