            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Okay thanks for checking. Could you try this which is closer to the original problem:\n```cython\n# cython: language_level=3\n\ncdef class IntLike:\n    cdef int value\n\n    def __init__(self, int value):\n        self.value = value\n\n    def __repr__(self):\n        return f\"IntLike({self.value})\"\n\n    def __int__(self):\n        return self.value\n\n    def __index__(self):\n        return self.value\n\n    def __richcmp__(self, other, int op):\n        other = int(other)\n        if op == 0:      # <\n            return self.value < other\n        elif op == 1:    # <=\n            return self.value <= other\n        elif op == 2:    # ==\n            return self.value == other\n        elif op == 3:    # !=\n            return self.value != other\n        elif op == 4:    # >\n            return self.value > other\n        elif op == 5:    # >=\n            return self.value >= other\n        return NotImplemented\n\ndef check(N: list[int]):\n    if any(n < 0 for n in N):\n        raise ValueError(\"all inflate strides must be non-negative\")\n    return \"ok\"\n\ncheck([IntLike(2), IntLike(3)])\n```\nWith Cython 3.3.0a1 it fails with `ValueError: all inflate strides must be non-negative` whereas with Cython 3.2.6 it runs to completion with no error. So it doesn't give a segfault but I think the code that Cython generates for the `check` function is not equivalent to the Python code shown.\n\nThe annotation says `list[int]` but what is being passed in is a list of int-like things. Potentially that should raise a TypeError somewhere but it should not fail with the ValueError shown.",
